V  We re-evaluate the matrix element for the proton-proton reaction which is\u000aimportant for stellar-evolution calculations and for the solar-neutrino\u000aproblem. We self-consistently determine the effect of vacuum polarization on\u000athe matrix element by first correcting the low-energy scattering data to\u000aaccount for vacuum polarization. We then calculate the proton-proton wave\u000afunction by integrating the Schrodinger equation with vacuum polarization\u000aincluded. We use improved data for proton-proton scattering and for the\u000adeuteron wave function. We evaluate the uncertainties that are due to\u000aexperimental error and estimate those that are due to theoretical inadequacies.\u000aWe estimate the theoretical uncertainty by using six different deuteron\u000apotentials and five different proton-proton potentials. Vacuum polarization\u000adecreases the calculated value by $0.6_{-0.4}^{+0.1}$\u005c%. The complete result is\u000a$\u005cLambda^2=6.92\u005ctimes(1\u005cpm0.002^{+0.014}_{-0.009})$ where the first uncertainty\u000ais due to experimental errors and the second uncertainty is due to theoretical\u000auncertainties. Our value of $\u005cLambda^2$ is 2\u005c% smaller than the value obtained\u000ain 1969 by Bahcall and May. The improved calculations of the rate of the $pp$\u000areaction described here increase slightly the predicted event rates for the\u000achlorine and the Kamiokande solar-neutrino experiments.\u000a
