V  Usually inflation ends either by a slow rolling of the inflaton field, which\u000agradually becomes faster and faster, or by a first-order phase transition. We\u000adescribe a model where inflation ends in a different way, due to a very rapid\u000arolling (`waterfall') of a scalar field $\u005csigma$ triggered by another scalar\u000afield $\u005cphi$. This model looks as a hybrid of chaotic inflation and the usual\u000atheory with spontaneous symmetry breaking. Another hybrid model to be discussed\u000ahere uses some building blocks from extended inflation (Brans-Dicke theory),\u000afrom new inflation (phase transition due to a non-minimal coupling of the\u000ainflaton field to gravity) and from chaotic inflation (the possibility of\u000ainflation beginning at large as well as at small $\u005csigma$). In the simplest\u000aversion of this scenario inflation ends up by slow rolling, thus avoiding the\u000abig-bubble problem of extended inflation.\u000a
